article.description:
Diana Taurasi led six Mercury players in double figures with 25
points to help keep Phoenix's playoff hopes alive in a 112-84 win
over the Charlotte Sting Thursday night.
article.headline: Mercury point their way toward last playoff spot
article.linkText: Mercury point their way toward last playoff spot
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Mercury executed coach Paul
Westhead's system to near-perfection, keeping them in the playoff
hunt.

Diana Taurasi led six Mercury players in double figures with 25
points to help keep Phoenix's playoff hopes alive in a 112-84 win
over the Charlotte Sting Thursday night.

"Everything we worked on the whole year kind of appeared
today," Taurasi said. "It was nice to see a lot of big games. I
think the moon's were lined up and sometimes you have nights like
this."

The win, coupled with San Antonio's loss to Sacramento earlier
Thursday, put Phoenix (13-16) into sole possession of fifth place
in the Western Conference, 2½ games behind Seattle for the fourth
and final postseason berth with five games to play.

"The fact that we won tonight means we are probably still alive
until we lose," Westhead said.

The Mercury set franchise records for points in a half (57) and
in a game, just missing a league record.

The WNBA record for points in a game is 114 by Minnesota against
Los Angeles on May 31. The Mercury tied the all-time league best
with 42 field goals.

"It was a good exhibition of fast-paced basketball," Westhead
said of his team's season-best 42 of 68 (61.8 percent) night from
the floor.

Monique Currie scored 19 points to lead Charlotte (9-21), which
has lost five of its last seven. Kelly Mazzante added 18.

Charlotte was as close as five in the final minute of the second
quarter but they never rallied.

"Second half, we just didn't show up," Charlotte coach Muggsy
Bogues said. "Make no excuses, but our center (Tammy Sutton-Brown)
went down and she was out. But whoever is in there has to do the
job and produce and we just didn't do that."

Sutton-Brown played just 14 minutes after experiencing lower
back spasms, team officials said.

The Mercury made three of their first four shots of the second
half, sparking a 13-3 run that gave Phoenix a 68-49 advantage with
5:34 left in the third quarter.

"I didn't think we lost focus but we had a lot of breakdowns on
defense," Mazzante said. "They were scoring from everywhere on
the floor."

Kelly Miller added 16 points and six assists as the Mercury
overcame a slow start on the boards. Charlotte grabbed 11 of the
first 13 rebounds but never had a lead after the first two minutes.

The Mercury, which broke their franchise point record of 96 with
5:51 remaining, have won twice since losing four straight.

Jennifer Lacy scored 16 points for Phoenix in 18 minutes and
Belinda Snell added 14.

"I didn't have to do a lot of play action calls because we were
getting shots off the break," Westhead said. "We can get better
at it and we didn't have the speed of our bigs that can really help
our fast-break game."

Taurasi scored 16 points and Miller added 12 to lead Phoenix to
a 55-46 at the break, their largest advantage up to that point.

A 9-2 spurt midway through the second quarter gave Phoenix some
momentum to post their highest scoring first half in franchise
history.
